12pt hep-th/0303139 
RUNHETC-2003-03 
  
Closed strings from decaying D-branes    


Neil  Lambert,  Hong Liu and Juan Maldacena 
 Department of Physics, Rutgers University 
Piscataway, New Jersey, 08855-0849 

 Institute for Advanced Study 
Princeton, New Jersey, 08540 

.3cm

We compute the emission of closed string radiation from
homogeneous rolling tachyons. For an unstable decaying D-brane
the radiated energy is infinite to leading order for  and
finite for . The closed string state produced by a decaying
brane is closely related to the state produced by D-instantons at
a critical Euclidean distance from . In the case of a D0
brane one can cutoff this divergence so that we get a finite
energy final state which would be the state that the brane decays
into.


April 21, 2003 















Introduction 


A D-brane in Bosonic string theory is unstable due to the
presence of an open string tachyon in its spectrum. If we displace
the tachyon  away from the maximum it will start rolling down the
potential toward the minimum, which is the closed string
vacuum  . It is of great interest to understand the
"real time" behavior of this
process  For one
thing, exact time-dependent solutions in string theory are hard to
come by and studying them should yield important insights into the
fundamental structure of the theory. We would also like to
understand the final state an unstable D-brane decays into.


Analysis by Sen at the classical level in open string theory  has yielded
some interesting surprises , .
It was found that
the late time evolution of the tachyon leads to a pressureless
fluid,  called "tachyon matter" (see however ).
Tachyon matter therefore seems to be a
new and unexpected  degree of freedom.
Hence it is natural
to understand the precise nature of tachyon matter
and in particular to take



into account the open and closed
strings created by the decay process.

In , 
 quantum creation of open strings was computed and it was argued that
this effect would
destabilize the
classical solution (see also ).

In this paper we are interested in computing the creation of closed
string modes from the rolling tachyon process.
Radiation produced by the rolling tachyon has been
discussed previously  in ,  for the massless closed
string modes. In addition supergravity solutions with rolling tachyon sources were discussed
in , . We will extend this to all massive closed string modes.
In ,,  it was observed that
the "rolling tachyon"  boundary state contains  exponentially increasing
couplings to massive closed string
modes and it was suggested in , 
that these will lead to pathelogical behaviour.
However  we will see that these couplings
are not relevant for the creation of on-shell physical  modes.
We find that the emission into on-shell physical closed string modes
is finite for each level. When we sum over all levels we find a
divergence in the emitted energy for  (similar conclusion
has also been reached in  ).
We also find a divergence if  and the worldvolume of the brane
is compact with a size comparable to the string scale.
The  case is
particularly interesting since  the computation
 suggests that all the energy of the initial brane is transfered
into closed string modes.
The  case is particularly relevant for applications 
to brane world cosmological models. 

It turns out that the precise closed string states that are
emitted from the brane depend on the physical interpretation of
the Sen's solution. We discuss two possible interpretations. The
first is the one implicitly advocated
in ,,  where one thinks of a tachyon field
coming up from its true minimum to a point close to the local
maximum associated to the unstable D-brane and then back to its
true minimum.  The second interpretation of the solution is more
closely related to the Euclidean computations. Here we cut the
Euclidean path integral at  and paste it to the Lorentzian
path integral. In this way the Euclidean path integral is viewed
as a prescription for setting up initial conditions at . The
subsequent Lorentzian evolution is the one resulting from these
initial conditions. In this interpretation the Euclidean
computations are more directly related to the Lorentzian ones. In
this case the closed string radiation that comes out of a decaying
brane is basically identical to the state at  of the
Euclidean path integral with some D-instantons added at a critical
Euclidean distance from the  plane.



In section 2 we review Sen's description of the boundary state and
compute the closed string radiation. In section 3 we explain that
the closed string states can be viewed as being produced by
D-instantons that are sitting at a critical distance in the
Euclidean direction. Section three has some overlap with the
discussion in .
In section 4 we describe some attempts at
computing the backreaction. We have included a few Appendices. In
Appendix A we give a second quantized description of various
formulae given in the main text.


In Appendix B we describe an effective field theory model for the
closed string creation following the discussion of . In
Appendix C, as a warmup for the backreaction question, we discuss
a simple example of the problem of finding the deformation of a
boundary state due to a closed string deformation of the
background.






 Closed string emission from a rolling tachyon 

Review of Sen's computation 

The decay of a Bosonic D-brane was described in  as a
boundary conformal field theory which is the usual non-decaying
D-brane plus a boundary interaction of the form
 
 S_bdy  =  _=0  d 
 X^0 () ,
  
where we have set the boundary of the worldsheet at 
and we have set . This tachyon profile is interpreted as
a configuration where the tachyon comes up from

the minimum associated with the closed string vacuum,
gets closest to zero at  and then  rolls back.

Other authors ,,  have
also discussed a seemingly more realistic process where we have a boundary
interaction of the form
 
 S_bdy ^half  = _=0  d  e^X^0 ()   ,
  
that describes the unstable brane at early times which then decays.
We will call  the full-S-brane and
 the half-S-brane.

The boundary state for a D-brane with boundary
interaction  takes the form
 
  B_p   B_X^0 
 B_X   B_bc  ,
  
where the normalization constant

_p = ^112 (2)^6-p  ,
 
is the same as that for a non-decaying  D-brane (corresponding to
