for the full-brane and half-brane respectively.

Some essential aspects of the boundary state  can be summarized
as follows ,,, :

1.  If  the
system becomes singular at a finite value of ,
as can be seen  from This is interpreted as due to the fact that the potential
is unbounded from below in Bosonic string theory and the tachyon can
run off on the "wrong side", i.e.  away from the closed string
vacuum.
This does not occur in the more realistic case of the superstring.
In this paper we restrict to .


2.  For the half-brane  is not a parameter, it can be set
to  by a time translation. The full-brane system is periodic in
 and  it can be restricted to lie between .
The half-brane can be obtained from the full-brane as a limit of 
along with a time translation.

3.  For the full-brane,  

at , the boundary
state vanishes identically for real values of time. This can be
interpreted as saying that
the system sits at the closed string vacuum. For  lying between  and
, the larger the value, the further away the turning point is from
the top of the tachyon potential.

4.  During the rolling process the energy is conserved and the stress
tensor of the system can be written as

T_00   = T_p ((t) + (t)) ,
T_ij  = - T_p (t) _ij  ,
 
where  denote spatial directions of the worldvolume and all
other components of the stress tensor vanish. In   is the
tension of a Dp-brane and  are given by It follows from that as , ,
i.e.  the system becomes pressureless.

