Closed string radiation 

A D-brane acts as a source for  closed string modes. With a
rolling tachyon  the  D-brane becomes a time-dependent 
source. Thus generically there will be closed string creation from the rolling
process. If we ignore the interactions between closed strings,
the question then reduces to the familiar problem of free particle production
by a time-dependent source. The created state is a coherent state.
Schematically, if  is the creation operator for
a physical  closed string mode, then the closed string state at late times
is proportional to
 where  is essentially
the one-point amplitude of the closed string mode on the disk.
More precisely,

 2 E  = A  = _p  V _disk  ,
 
where  is the spacetime energy of the state and
 is the corresponding on-shell vertex operator.
 is the normalization factor .
Notice that this is a process which is of order .

It is possible to show that for any physical on-shell closed
string state with nonzero   energy we can choose a gauge
where there are no timelike oscillators, see . In such a
gauge the full vertex operator for an on-shell closed string state
can be chosen to be of the form
  
  V = e^  i E X^0  V_sp 
   
 where  is made out of the 25 spatial fields. This is
 equivalent to the statement that we can choose a gauge where we
 can put all the  oscillators to zero.
 It should be noted that the vertex operator  is
 constrained to be a Virasoro primary state of arbitrary conformal
 weight . The  constraint gives us the value of the
 energy  in terms of , .
The gauge  is very convenient since the computation of the
one point function factorizes as
 
 V _disk  = e^iE X^0  _X^0    V_sp  _sp 
  
 into a product of the one point function for the time part and
 a one point function for the rest.



The computation of the second factor in
  is straightforward and it is
 given by the inner product of the spatial part of the boundary
 state, which is the spatial part of a standard D-brane,
 
with  the closed string state under consideration.
The spatial part of the boundary state has the form, up to an overall
constant,
 
  d^25-p  k  _H_L 
   e^i ()   _L  _R k .
   
Note that the boundary state is such that we have the same
 oscillator state for  the right and left movers, up to a phase
that is irrelevant for our computations. We also have a sum over
all possible oscillator states we can make with the left movers.
So the counting of states is the same as the counting for
 an open string.
Finally, all states appearing in  are unit normalized.

We can separate the closed string Hilbert space into
states that are left right identical, as in  and
the orthogonal complement. So only states in the first subspace
will be emitted. If we take
 
the overlap with
 is just a phase.

Therefore, it follows from  that up to a phase,   can be
identified with  the disk one point function
for an operator of the form 

 A  =
  _p  I(E) =  _p  e^i  E X^0  _disk   .
 
To evaluate  it is convenient to
separate the zero mode integration  with the decomposition
 and we have

I(E) = e^i  E X^0  _disk  = _  dt  e^ i Et  
e^i  E X^0  _disk   .
 
Note that in performing the
zero mode integration one has to specify a contour .
The computation
of  essentially reduces (almost by definition)
to that of computing
the first term in . Thus we find that

I (E) = i _C   dt  (t)  e^ i E t 
 
where  is given by   or .
In order to determine the contour  we need some more
physical information.
The most obvious choice of contour is to take it
to run  along the real axis . We call
this the real   contour, .
This contour corresponds to interpreting the full-brane
as a configuration where the tachyon rises up to a value closest
to zero and then decays back again. Having the tachyon rise in this
way in the full theory involves some fine-tuning  which
we do not worry about here. For the half-brane it is necessary
to rotate   in order to make
the integral convergent. This corresponds to the standard choice
of vacuum for closed strings, i.e.  there is no incoming radiation
from .

Since  the full-brane interaction  is time symmetric around
, there is another
interesting contour which we will call the
Hartle-Hawking  contour, . This contour runs from
 along the imaginary axis
to  and then along the real axis to .
We can imagine the contour along the imaginary axis as preparing
the state at . If we did this in a field theory in the bulk
the path integral up to  along the imaginary axis would
produce a state at . This state would be the vacuum if there
were no brane. When there is a brane the state is not the vacuum
but some other state produced by the brane. We then evolve this
state for  along the real axis.
Note that this prescription also creates a state  for the open
string modes on the brane. This is the  state
that we naturally get if we blindly
analytically continue the Euclidean expressions. We will elaborate more
about the physical interpretation of the Hartle-Hawking  contour
in the next section.




The integral  for the different contours gives

i_C _real    dt  _full (t)  e^ i E t   = &
(e^-i E    -  e^i E   )  E   ,
i_C _real    dt  _half (t)  e^ i E t   = &
 e^- i E    E   ,
i_C_HH    dt  _full (t)  e^ i E t   = &
  e^- i E    E   .
  
The two exponentials in the first line of  can
be interpreted as  the
radiation emitted in the rising  part of the full-brane and
the decaying part of the full-brane. Note
that the  dependence for the half brane
is precisely what we expect on the basis of time
translation invariance.

Surprisingly, the result for the full-brane using the
Hartle-Hawking contour gives the same result as the half-brane.
   From  and  this implies that, up to a phase due to time
translation, the final closed string state produced by
the half-brane is the same as that produced by the full-brane
using the Hartle-Hawking  contour.
Since  only appears  in the  phase, the closed string
states with
different values of  only differ by an
overall time translation.  For the half-brane this is a trivial  consequence of the fact that
changing  is the same as performing a time translation,
 but for the full-brane with  this is surprising.
Note that the Hartle-Hawking presciption leads to a time symmetric
state. So we have radiation coming in from  and being
absorbed by the brane. For  we have no D-brane
and this radiation that comes from  just reflects from
the origin and goes out.
 In contrast,
for the full-brane with the real contour,
the absolute value of the amplitude
is  dependent and vanishes at .
For  we see that the closed strings  produced by the
rising phase and decaying phase is moved
all the way to .



Note also that the contour that is natural in the Euclidean theory,
which runs along the imaginary axis, would be badly divergent for
real .
Nevertheless  are analytic in  and when 
they have a pole. We see that the residue of the pole for the
Hartle-Hawking countour or the half-brane has the values we get
in the Euclidean computation. The fact that there is a pole
is related to the fact that the Euclidean computation for 
has a divergent volume factor, the volume of Euclidean time.
 Note that that the residue of the
pole for the real contour is not  the same as the result for
the Euclidean computation. As we explained above the Euclidean
computation is more directly related to the Hartle-Hawking
contour.



In conclusion the emission amplitude for this closed string state
will be given by the integrals  with  equal to the
spacetime energy of the state.


Now we compute the total average number and the total energy of
particles emitted.
