D-instantons and the closed string final state 


There is a very beautiful and simple description
of the closed string state that is produced by the full-brane
with the Hartle-Hawking contour or the half-braneThis discussion
has some overlap with the discussion in , where these
issues are discussed in more detail. .
 As we explained
above the state that is produced is a coherent state in the space
of closed string fields. Let us think for the moment about the
bulk closed string field theory as an ordinary field theory.
A method for producing coherent states is to perform the path integral
in Euclidean space with a source
and cut this path integral at . The result
of the path integral is a function of the boundary
values of the fields at
. We can think of this function as a wavefunction for the fields.
For example, the wavefunction of the vacuum is obtained by doing the
path integral over negative  imaginary Euclidean time.
If we insert operators or sources
at Euclidean times  this same
path integral will  produce a different state.

For simpliticy let us start by discussing the state that we get if
we insert a D-instanton at a distance  from  (see fig. 2).
This will act as a point source for many closed string fields
which at  will have an amplitude of the form
 where  is the energy of the particular closed
string mode. The norm of the state involves squaring the
amplitude and summing over all states. The terms in this
 sum  go as  for large . So
see that if  the state that we produce in this way is not
normalizable.
Therefore the approximation in which we derived
it is not valid and we do not trust the resulting state.
On the other hand if , the state that we create in this
fashion is a perfectly nice and normalizable finite energy state
in the field theory of closed string modes and has an energy of order
one (i.e.  ).
We can understand this change in behaviour as follows.
We can compute the norm of the state produced in the above way by
considering the path integral over  full Euclidean time were
we put sources at  in a time reflection symmetric fashion.
The divergence in the norm is related to the
fact that the open string going between the D-instanton at  and
the one at  becomes tachyonic precisely at .
So this divergence is  rather similar to
the Hagedorn divergence. Note, however, that the state that is produced
in this fashion is not thermal, it is a pure state.




